NI DAQ card architecture

NI DAQ cards are hardware devices that allow computers to acquire and generate analog and digital signals. They act as an interface between the physical world (sensors, actuators, etc.) and the computer. NI DAQ cards can be implemented in different formfactors. In our microscopes they are implemented as PCI Express cards, inserted into the rig computers.

The schematics for the NI DAQ card system architecture.

Computer (CPU, Memory, Expansion Slot)
|
+-- DAQ Card (ADC, DAC, DIO, Counter/Timer, Connector)
|
+-- Cable
|
+-- Breakout Board (Connector, Terminals/Connectors)
|
+-- External Devices (Sensors, Actuators)

General Overview of the components.

1. Computer:

  • CPU: The central processing unit, responsible for executing instructions and processing data.
  • Memory (RAM): Stores data temporarily for the CPU to access.
  • Expansion Slot: Where the DAQ card is inserted (e.g., PCI, PCIe, USB).
  • Operating System: Provides the interface between the hardware and software.

2. DAQ Card:

  • Analog-to-Digital Converter (ADC): Converts analog signals (like voltage or current) into digital values that the computer can understand.
  • Digital-to-Analog Converter (DAC): Converts digital signals from the computer into analog signals.
  • Digital Input/Output (DIO) Ports: Allow for communication with digital devices.
  • Counter/Timer: Enables precise timing measurements and control.
  • Connector: Connects the DAQ card to the breakout board.

3. Breakout Board:

  • Connector: Matches the connector on the DAQ card.
  • Terminals or Connectors: Provide access to the DAQ card's signals (analog inputs/outputs, digital I/O, etc.).
  • Often includes:
    • Screw terminals: For easy connection of wires.
    • BNC connectors: For connecting to common laboratory equipment.
    • Other connectors: Depending on the specific application (e.g., BNC, terminal blocks, etc.).

Connections:

  • The DAQ card is inserted into the expansion slot of the computer.
  • The breakout board is connected to the DAQ card using a suitable cable (often provided with the DAQ card).
  • External devices (sensors, actuators, etc.) are connected to the terminals or connectors on the breakout board.

Software nomenclature

While the detailed description of different connections present on a breakout board is DAQ card and breakout board specific, and is beyond the scope of this overview, here is a typical example of what you might encounter in our microscope software.

Consider the following address on the DAQ card: Dev1/port0/line2.

  • Dev1 -- refers to the device ID or the name assigned to the specific DAQ card. It helps distinguish between multiple DAQ cards that might be installed in the system.
  • port0 -- indicates a specific port or module on the DAQ card. Many DAQ cards have multiple ports, each containing a set of input/output lines.
  • line2 -- specifies the individual line or channel within that particular port and, ultimately, the physical connection to which one connects a wire.

Breakout board / terminal block

As an example, below is the NI SCB-68A connector terminal block connected to the NI 6374 DAQ card. Since the terminal block is designed to be able to be connected to different DAQ cards, the line-terminal correspondence is different for these cards. This is correspondence can be found in this pinout documentation (look for the label for the specific DAQ card, NI 6374 in this example). You'll notice there different types of pin labels. In our microscopes, the pinout diagram is attached to the back side of the connector block cover.

There are different ground pins for different types of connections (AI -- analog input, AO -- analog output, D GRD -- digital ground), AI # labels analog input pins, AO # labels analog output pins, PFI -- programmable function interfaces, and P#.# digital labels ports and lines. For more, see Pinout Terminology and Definitions for NI DAQ Devices.

So, in the picture below, the circled green wire is connected to the pin 43 -- P0.3. And since this DAQ card happens to named DEV3 in this particular rig computer, the full address to this pin in the computer software is DEV3/port0/line3. You can control this pin from either a custom written, or from the NI MAX (Measurement and Automation) software.
